                <div class="card faq-section">
                    <div class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much protein do I need per day?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">The recommended daily protein intake depends on your goals and activity level. Sedentary adults need about 0.8g per kg (0.36g per lb) of body weight. For muscle gain, aim for 1.6&ndash;2.2g per kg (0.73&ndash;1.0g per lb). For fat loss while preserving muscle, 1.8&ndash;2.4g per kg (0.82&ndash;1.1g per lb) is recommended. Endurance athletes should target 1.2&ndash;1.6g per kg (0.55&ndash;0.73g per lb).</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can you eat too much protein?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">For healthy individuals, protein intakes up to 2.2g per kg of body weight are well-studied and safe. Very high protein diets (above 3g per kg) have not shown adverse effects in healthy people in short-term studies, but long-term data is limited. People with kidney disease should consult their doctor before increasing protein intake.</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">When should I eat protein for muscle growth?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Distribute protein evenly across 3&ndash;6 meals (20&ndash;40g per meal) to maximize muscle protein synthesis. Consume protein within 2 hours after resistance training. A protein-rich meal or shake before bed (30&ndash;40g casein or mixed protein) can support overnight muscle recovery. Pre-workout protein 1&ndash;2 hours before training also helps.</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What are the best sources of protein?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">The best protein sources are complete proteins containing all essential amino acids: chicken breast (31g per 100g), eggs (6g per egg), Greek yogurt (10g per 100g), salmon (25g per 100g), lean beef (26g per 100g), and whey protein (25g per scoop). Plant-based options include tofu, lentils, chickpeas, and tempeh.</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does protein help with weight loss?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes. Protein is the most satiating macronutrient &mdash; it keeps you full longer and reduces cravings. It also has the highest thermic effect of food (20&ndash;30% of protein calories are burned during digestion). Higher protein intake during a caloric deficit helps preserve lean muscle mass, which keeps your metabolism higher.</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much protein can your body absorb per meal?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Your body can digest and absorb virtually unlimited protein per meal &mdash; the myth of a &lsquo;30g limit&rsquo; is outdated. However, muscle protein synthesis is optimally stimulated by 20&ndash;40g of high-quality protein per meal. Eating more than 40g per sitting still contributes to overall daily protein needs, but the muscle-building stimulus does not increase proportionally.</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do I need more protein as I get older?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes. Adults over 50 have higher protein needs due to age-related muscle loss (sarcopenia) and reduced protein synthesis efficiency. Older adults should aim for 1.0&ndash;1.2g per kg of body weight even if sedentary, and 1.2&ndash;1.6g per kg if active. Distributing protein evenly across meals becomes even more important with age.</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is protein powder necessary?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Protein powder is not necessary if you can meet your daily protein target through whole foods. However, it is a convenient and cost-effective way to increase intake, especially for people with high protein needs (above 150g/day) or busy schedules. Whey protein is the most researched and effective supplement for muscle building.</div></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="seo-content">
            <h2>How Much Protein Do You Need Per Day?</h2>
            <p>Your daily protein requirement depends on your body weight, fitness goals, and how active you are. The RDA of 0.8g per kilogram is the minimum to prevent deficiency in sedentary adults &mdash; not the optimal amount for people who exercise, want to build muscle, or are trying to lose fat while preserving lean mass.</p>
            <p>Research consistently shows that higher protein intakes (1.6&ndash;2.2g per kg) are more effective for body composition goals. This protein calculator uses evidence-based multipliers adjusted for your specific goal and activity level to give you a personalized recommendation.</p>

            <h2>Protein for Muscle Gain vs. Fat Loss</h2>
            <p>For muscle gain, protein provides the amino acids needed for muscle protein synthesis. The optimal range is 1.6&ndash;2.2g per kg of body weight, spread across 3&ndash;6 meals throughout the day. Going above 2.2g per kg provides diminishing returns for most people.</p>
            <p>For fat loss, protein needs are actually higher than for muscle gain &mdash; typically 1.8&ndash;2.4g per kg. When you are in a caloric deficit, your body is more likely to break down muscle for energy. A higher protein intake signals your body to preserve lean tissue, keeping your metabolism higher and improving the quality of weight lost.</p>

            <h2>Protein Timing and Distribution</h2>
            <p>While total daily protein intake matters most, research suggests spreading protein evenly across meals optimizes muscle protein synthesis. Each meal should contain at least 20&ndash;40g of protein to fully stimulate the muscle-building response. Pre- and post-workout protein (within 1&ndash;2 hours of training) and a protein-rich snack before bed can further enhance recovery and growth.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Pre-workout (1&ndash;2 hours before):</strong> 20&ndash;30g protein with slow-digesting carbs for sustained energy and amino acid availability during training.</li>
                <li><strong>Post-workout (within 2 hours):</strong> 25&ndash;40g fast-digesting protein (whey, eggs) paired with carbs to kick-start recovery and glycogen replenishment.</li>
                <li><strong>Before bed (30&ndash;60 minutes prior):</strong> 30&ndash;40g slow-digesting protein (casein, cottage cheese) to support overnight muscle repair.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </main>
</div>

<script is:inline>
let currentUnit = 'imperial';
let mealCount = 4;
let dailyProtein = 0;

function setUnit(unit) {
    currentUnit = unit;
    document.getElementById('btnMetric').classList.toggle('active', unit === 'metric');
    document.getElementById('btnImperial').classList.toggle('active', unit === 'imperial');
    document.querySelectorAll('.metric-inputs').forEach(el => el.style.display = unit === 'metric' ? '' : 'none');
    document.querySelectorAll('.imperial-inputs').forEach(el => el.style.display = unit === 'imperial' ? '' : 'none');

    if (unit === 'metric') {
        document.getElementById('weightKg').required = true;
        document.getElementById('weightLbs').required = false;
    } else {
        document.getElementById('weightKg').required = false;
        document.getElementById('weightLbs').required = true;
    }
}

setUnit('imperial');

const multipliers = {
    maintain: {
        sedentary:  [0.8, 1.0],
        light:      [1.0, 1.2],
        moderate:   [1.0, 1.4],
        very:       [1.2, 1.6],
        extreme:    [1.4, 1.8]
    },
    muscle: {
        sedentary:  [1.4, 1.6],
        light:      [1.6, 1.8],
        moderate:   [1.6, 2.0],
        very:       [1.8, 2.2],
        extreme:    [2.0, 2.4]
    },
    fatloss: {
        sedentary:  [1.2, 1.6],
        light:      [1.6, 2.0],
        moderate:   [1.8, 2.2],
        very:       [2.0, 2.4],
        extreme:    [2.0, 2.4]
    },
    endurance: {
        sedentary:  [1.0, 1.2],
        light:      [1.2, 1.4],
        moderate:   [1.2, 1.6],
        very:       [1.4, 1.8],
        extreme:    [1.6, 2.0]
    }
};

const goalLabels = {
    maintain: 'Maintenance',
    muscle: 'Muscle Gain',
    fatloss: 'Fat Loss',
    endurance: 'Endurance'
};

document.getElementById('proteinForm').addEventListener('submit', function(e) {
    e.preventDefault();
    calculate();
});

function calculate() {
    let weightKg;
    if (currentUnit === 'metric') {
        weightKg = parseFloat(document.getElementById('weightKg').value);
    } else {
        const lbs = parseFloat(document.getElementById('weightLbs').value);
        weightKg = lbs / 2.205;
    }

    if (!weightKg || weightKg <= 0) return;

    const goal = document.getElementById('goal').value;
    const activity = document.getElementById('activity').value;
    const [low, high] = multipliers[goal][activity];

    const proteinLow = Math.round(weightKg * low);
    const proteinHigh = Math.round(weightKg * high);
    dailyProtein = Math.round((proteinLow + proteinHigh) / 2);

    const weightLb = weightKg * 2.205;
    const perKg = (dailyProtein / weightKg).toFixed(1);
    const perLb = (dailyProtein / weightLb).toFixed(2);
    const perMeal = Math.round(dailyProtein / mealCount);

    document.getElementById('proteinValue').textContent = dailyProtein + 'g';
    document.getElementById('rangeLabel').textContent = goalLabels[goal] + ' \u2022 ' + proteinLow + '\u2013' + proteinHigh + 'g range';

    document.getElementById('statDaily').textContent = dailyProtein + 'g';
    document.getElementById('statRange').textContent = proteinLow + '\u2013' + proteinHigh + 'g range';
    document.getElementById('statPerKg').textContent = perKg + 'g';
    document.getElementById('statPerLb').textContent = perLb + 'g';
    document.getElementById('statPerMeal').textContent = perMeal + 'g';
    document.getElementById('statMealCount').textContent = 'across ' + mealCount + ' meals';

    updateMealChart();
    updateTiming();

    document.getElementById('results').classList.add('active');
}

function setMeals(n) {
    mealCount = n;
    document.querySelectorAll('.meal-count-btn').forEach(btn => {
        btn.classList.toggle('active', parseInt(btn.dataset.meals) === n);
    });
    if (dailyProtein > 0) {
        const perMeal = Math.round(dailyProtein / mealCount);
        document.getElementById('statPerMeal').textContent = perMeal + 'g';
        document.getElementById('statMealCount').textContent = 'across ' + mealCount + ' meals';
        updateMealChart();
    }
}

function updateMealChart() {
    const chart = document.getElementById('mealChart');
    chart.innerHTML = '';

    const mealNames = {
        3: ['Breakfast', 'Lunch', 'Dinner'],
        4: ['Breakfast', 'Lunch', 'Snack', 'Dinner'],
        5: ['Breakfast', 'Snack', 'Lunch', 'Snack', 'Dinner'],
        6: ['Breakfast', 'Snack', 'Lunch', 'Snack', 'Dinner', 'Before Bed']
    };

    const names = mealNames[mealCount];
    const perMeal = Math.round(dailyProtein / mealCount);
    const maxVal = perMeal * 1.2;

    for (let i = 0; i < mealCount; i++) {
        const wrapper = document.createElement('div');
        wrapper.className = 'meal-bar-wrapper';

        const val = document.createElement('div');
        val.className = 'meal-bar-value';
        val.textContent = perMeal + 'g';

        const bar = document.createElement('div');
        bar.className = 'meal-bar';
        const pct = Math.max(10, (perMeal / maxVal) * 100);
        bar.style.height = pct + '%';

        const label = document.createElement('div');
        label.className = 'meal-bar-label';
        label.textContent = names[i];

        wrapper.appendChild(val);
        wrapper.appendChild(bar);
        wrapper.appendChild(label);
        chart.appendChild(wrapper);
    }
}

function updateTiming() {
    const pre = Math.round(dailyProtein * 0.15);
    const post = Math.round(dailyProtein * 0.2);
    const bed = Math.round(dailyProtein * 0.18);

    document.getElementById('timingPre').textContent = pre + 'g';
    document.getElementById('timingPost').textContent = post + 'g';
    document.getElementById('timingBed').textContent = bed + 'g';
}

function toggleFaq(btn) {
    const item = btn.parentElement;
    item.classList.toggle('open');
}
</script>

</SiteLayout>
